/*
------------------------------------------------------------
ğŸ§  Problem: Detect Loop in a Linked List
------------------------------------------------------------
Given a linked list, the task is to determine whether the 
linked list contains a cycle (loop) or not.

A loop exists if there is a node in the list that can be 
reached again by continuously following the next pointer.

------------------------------------------------------------
ğŸ’¡ Approach: Floydâ€™s Cycle Detection Algorithm 
(Tortoise and Hare Algorithm)
------------------------------------------------------------
1ï¸âƒ£ Use two pointers:
    - `slow` moves one step at a time.
    - `fast` moves multiple steps at a time (here, 3 steps).

2ï¸âƒ£ If thereâ€™s a loop, both pointers will eventually meet 
   at some node inside the loop.

3ï¸âƒ£ If the `fast` pointer or its next pointer becomes NULL, 
   that means the list terminates â†’ No loop.

------------------------------------------------------------
â±ï¸ Time Complexity: O(N)
ğŸ“¦ Space Complexity: O(1)
------------------------------------------------------------
*/

class Solution {
  public:
    bool detectLoop(Node* head) {
        Node* slow = head, *fast = head->next;
        
        while (fast && fast->next && fast->next->next) {
            if (slow == fast)
                return true;
            slow = slow->next;
            fast = fast->next->next->next;
        }
        
        return false;
    }
};
